2879 /// has already been parsed if present. disp may be provided as well. ----
2880 bool X86AsmParser::ParseMemOperand(unsigned SegReg, const MCExpr *Disp, 0
2881 SMLoc StartLoc, SMLoc EndLoc, ----
2882 OperandVector &Operands) { ----
2883 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
2884 SMLoc Loc; 0
2885 // Based on the initial passed values, we may be in any of these cases, we are ----
2886 // in one of these cases (with current position (*)): ----
2887 ----
2888 // 1. seg : * disp (base-index-scale-expr) ----
2889 // 2. seg : *(disp) (base-index-scale-expr) ----
2890 // 3. seg : *(base-index-scale-expr) ----
2891 // 4. disp *(base-index-scale-expr) ----
2892 // 5. *(disp) (base-index-scale-expr) ----
2893 // 6. *(base-index-scale-expr) ----
2894 // 7. disp * ----
2895 // 8. *(disp) ----
2896 ----
2897 // If we do not have an displacement yet, check if we're in cases 4 or 6 by ----
2898 // checking if the first object after the parenthesis is a register (or an ----
2899 // identifier referring to a register) and parse the displacement or default ----
2900 // to 0 as appropriate. ----
2901 auto isAtMemOperand = [this]() { 0
2902 if (this->getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::LParen)) 0
2903 return false; 0
2904 AsmToken Buf[2]; 0
2905 StringRef Id; 0
2906 auto TokCount = this->getLexer().peekTokens(Buf, true); 0
2907 if (TokCount == 0) 0
2908 return false; 0
2909 switch (Buf[0].getKind()) { 0
2910 case AsmToken::Percent: 0
2911 case AsmToken::Comma: ----
2912 return true; 0
2913 // These lower cases are doing a peekIdentifier. ----
2914 case AsmToken::At: 0
2915 case AsmToken::Dollar: ----
2916 if ((TokCount > 1) && 0
2917 (Buf[1].is(AsmToken::Identifier) || Buf[1].is(AsmToken::String)) && 0
2918 (Buf[0].getLoc().getPointer() + 1 == Buf[1].getLoc().getPointer())) 0
2919 Id = StringRef(Buf[0].getLoc().getPointer(), 0
2920 Buf[1].getIdentifier().size() + 1); 0
2921 break; 0
2922 case AsmToken::Identifier: 0
2923 case AsmToken::String: ----
2924 Id = Buf[0].getIdentifier(); 0
2925 break; 0
2926 default: 0
2927 return false; 0
2928 } ----
2929 // We have an ID. Check if it is bound to a register. ----
2930 if (!Id.empty()) { 0
2931 MCSymbol *Sym = this->getContext().getOrCreateSymbol(Id); 0
2932 if (Sym->isVariable()) { 0
2933 auto V = Sym->getVariableValue(/*SetUsed*/ false); 0
2934 return isa(V); 0
2935 } ----
2936 } ----
2937 return false; 0
2938 }; 0
2939 ----
2940 if (!Disp) { 0
2941 // Parse immediate if we're not at a mem operand yet. ----
2942 if (!isAtMemOperand()) { 0
2943 if (Parser.parseTokenLoc(Loc) || Parser.parseExpression(Disp, EndLoc)) 0
2944 return true; 0
2945 assert(!isa(Disp) && "Expected non-register here."); 0
2946 } else { ----
2947 // Disp is implicitly zero if we haven't parsed it yet. ----
2948 Disp = MCConstantExpr::create(0, Parser.getContext()); 0
2949 } ----
2950 } ----
2951 ----
2952 // We are now either at the end of the operand or at the '(' at the start of a ----
2953 // base-index-scale-expr. ----
2954 ----
2955 if (!parseOptionalToken(AsmToken::LParen)) { 0
2956 if (SegReg == 0) 0
2957 Operands.push_back( 0
2958 X86Operand::CreateMem(getPointerWidth(), Disp, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
2959 else ----
2960 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateMem(getPointerWidth(), SegReg, Disp, 0
2961 0, 0, 1, StartLoc, EndLoc)); ----
2962 return false; 0
2963 } ----
2964 ----
2965 // If we reached here, then eat the '(' and Process ----
2966 // the rest of the memory operand. ----
2967 unsigned BaseReg = 0, IndexReg = 0, Scale = 1; 0
2968 SMLoc BaseLoc = getLexer().getLoc(); 0
2969 const MCExpr *E; ----
2970 StringRef ErrMsg; 0
2971 ----
2972 // Parse BaseReg if one is provided. ----
2973 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Comma) && getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::RParen)) { 0
2974 if (Parser.parseExpression(E, EndLoc) || 0
2975 check(!isa(E), BaseLoc, "expected register here")) 0
2976 return true; 0
2977 ----
2978 // Check the register. ----
2979 BaseReg = cast(E)->getRegNo(); 0
2980 if (BaseReg == X86::EIZ || BaseReg == X86::RIZ) 0
2981 return Error(BaseLoc, "eiz and riz can only be used as index registers", 0
2982 SMRange(BaseLoc, EndLoc)); 0
2983 } ----
2984 ----
2985 if (parseOptionalToken(AsmToken::Comma)) { 0
2986 // Following the comma we should have either an index register, or a scale ----
2987 // value. We don't support the later form, but we want to parse it ----
2988 // correctly. ----
2989 // ----
2990 // Even though it would be completely consistent to support syntax like ----
2991 // "1(%eax,,1)", the assembler doesn't. Use "eiz" or "riz" for this. ----
2992 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::RParen)) { 0
2993 if (Parser.parseTokenLoc(Loc) || Parser.parseExpression(E, EndLoc)) 0
2994 return true; 0
2995 ----
2996 if (!isa(E)) { 0
2997 // We've parsed an unexpected Scale Value instead of an index ----
2998 // register. Interpret it as an absolute. ----
2999 int64_t ScaleVal; ----
3000 if (!E->evaluateAsAbsolute(ScaleVal, getStreamer().getAssemblerPtr())) 0
3001 return Error(Loc, "expected absolute expression"); 0
3002 if (ScaleVal != 1) 0
3003 Warning(Loc, "scale factor without index register is ignored"); 0
3004 Scale = 1; 0
3005 } else { // IndexReg Found. ----
3006 IndexReg = cast(E)->getRegNo(); 0
3007 ----
3008 if (BaseReg == X86::RIP) 0
3009 return Error(Loc, 0
3010 "%rip as base register can not have an index register"); 0
3011 if (IndexReg == X86::RIP) 0
3012 return Error(Loc, "%rip is not allowed as an index register"); 0
3013 ----
3014 if (parseOptionalToken(AsmToken::Comma)) { 0
3015 // Parse the scale amount: ----
3016 // ::= ',' [scale-expression] ----
3017 ----
3018 // A scale amount without an index is ignored. ----
3019 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::RParen)) { 0
3020 int64_t ScaleVal; ----
3021 if (Parser.parseTokenLoc(Loc) || 0
3022 Parser.parseAbsoluteExpression(ScaleVal)) 0
3023 return Error(Loc, "expected scale expression"); 0
3024 Scale = (unsigned)ScaleVal; 0
3025 // Validate the scale amount. ----
3026 if (X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::GR16RegClassID].contains(BaseReg) && 0
3027 Scale != 1) ----
3028 return Error(Loc, "scale factor in 16-bit address must be 1"); 0
3029 if (checkScale(Scale, ErrMsg)) 0
3030 return Error(Loc, ErrMsg); 0
3031 } ----
3032 } ----
3033 } ----
3034 } ----
3035 } ----
3036 ----
3037 // Ok, we've eaten the memory operand, verify we have a ')' and eat it too. ----
3038 if (parseToken(AsmToken::RParen, "unexpected token in memory operand")) 0
3039 return true; 0
3040 ----
3041 // This is to support otherwise illegal operand (%dx) found in various ----
3042 // unofficial manuals examples (e.g. "out[s]?[bwl]? %al, (%dx)") and must now ----
3043 // be supported. Mark such DX variants separately fix only in special cases. ----
3044 if (BaseReg == X86::DX && IndexReg == 0 && Scale == 1 && SegReg == 0 && 0
3045 isa(Disp) && 0
3046 cast(Disp)->getValue() == 0) { 0
3047 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateDXReg(BaseLoc, BaseLoc)); 0
3048 return false; 0
3049 } ----
3050 ----
3051 if (CheckBaseRegAndIndexRegAndScale(BaseReg, IndexReg, Scale, is64BitMode(), 0
3052 ErrMsg)) ----
3053 return Error(BaseLoc, ErrMsg); 0
3054 ----
3055 if (SegReg || BaseReg || IndexReg) 0
3056 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateMem(getPointerWidth(), SegReg, Disp, 0
3057 BaseReg, IndexReg, Scale, StartLoc, ----
3058 EndLoc)); ----
3059 else ----
3060 Operands.push_back( 0
3061 X86Operand::CreateMem(getPointerWidth(), Disp, StartLoc, EndLoc)); 0
3062 return false; 0
3063 } ----
3064 ----
3065 // Parse either a standard primary expression or a register. ----
3066 bool X86AsmParser::parsePrimaryExpr(const MCExpr *&Res, SMLoc &EndLoc) { 0
3067 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
3068 // See if this is a register first. ----
3069 if (getTok().is(AsmToken::Percent) || 0
3070 (isParsingIntelSyntax() && getTok().is(AsmToken::Identifier) && 0
3071 MatchRegisterName(Parser.getTok().getString()))) { 0
3072 SMLoc StartLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
3073 MCRegister RegNo; 0
3074 if (parseRegister(RegNo, StartLoc, EndLoc)) 0
3075 return true; 0
3076 Res = X86MCExpr::create(RegNo, Parser.getContext()); 0
3077 return false; 0
3078 } ----
3079 return Parser.parsePrimaryExpr(Res, EndLoc, nullptr); 0
3080 } ----
3081 ----
3082 bool X86AsmParser::ParseInstruction(ParseInstructionInfo &Info, StringRef Name, 0
3083 SMLoc NameLoc, OperandVector &Operands) { ----
3084 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
3085 InstInfo = &Info; 0
3086 ----
3087 // Reset the forced VEX encoding. ----
3088 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_Default; 0
3089 ForcedDispEncoding = DispEncoding_Default; 0
3090 ----
3091 // Parse pseudo prefixes. ----
3092 while (true) { ----
3093 if (Name == "{") { 0
3094 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) 0
3095 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "Unexpected token after '{'"); 0
3096 std::string Prefix = Parser.getTok().getString().lower(); 0
3097 Parser.Lex(); // Eat identifier. 0
3098 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::RCurly)) 0
3099 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "Expected '}'"); 0
3100 Parser.Lex(); // Eat curly. 0
3101 ----
3102 if (Prefix == "vex") 0
3103 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX; 0
3104 else if (Prefix == "vex2") 0
3105 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX2; 0
3106 else if (Prefix == "vex3") 0
3107 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX3; 0
3108 else if (Prefix == "evex") 0
3109 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_EVEX; 0
3110 else if (Prefix == "disp8") 0
3111 ForcedDispEncoding = DispEncoding_Disp8; 0
3112 else if (Prefix == "disp32") 0
3113 ForcedDispEncoding = DispEncoding_Disp32; 0
3114 else ----
3115 return Error(NameLoc, "unknown prefix"); 0
3116 ----
3117 NameLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
3118 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::LCurly)) { 0
3119 Parser.Lex(); 0
3120 Name = "{"; 0
3121 } else { ----
3122 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) 0
3123 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "Expected identifier"); 0
3124 // FIXME: The mnemonic won't match correctly if its not in lower case. ----
3125 Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3126 Parser.Lex(); 0
3127 } ----
3128 continue; 0
3129 } 0
3130 // Parse MASM style pseudo prefixes. ----
3131 if (isParsingMSInlineAsm()) { 0
3132 if (Name.equals_insensitive("vex")) 0
3133 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX; 0
3134 else if (Name.equals_insensitive("vex2")) 0
3135 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX2; 0
3136 else if (Name.equals_insensitive("vex3")) 0
3137 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_VEX3; 0
3138 else if (Name.equals_insensitive("evex")) 0
3139 ForcedVEXEncoding = VEXEncoding_EVEX; 0
3140 ----
3141 if (ForcedVEXEncoding != VEXEncoding_Default) { 0
3142 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::Identifier)) 0
3143 return Error(Parser.getTok().getLoc(), "Expected identifier"); 0
3144 // FIXME: The mnemonic won't match correctly if its not in lower case. ----
3145 Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3146 NameLoc = Parser.getTok().getLoc(); 0
3147 Parser.Lex(); 0
3148 } ----
3149 } ----
3150 break; 0
3151 } 0
3152 ----
3153 // Support the suffix syntax for overriding displacement size as well. ----
3154 if (Name.consume_back(".d32")) { 0
3155 ForcedDispEncoding = DispEncoding_Disp32; 0
3156 } else if (Name.consume_back(".d8")) { 0
3157 ForcedDispEncoding = DispEncoding_Disp8; 0
3158 } ----
3159 ----
3160 StringRef PatchedName = Name; 0
3161 ----
3162 // Hack to skip "short" following Jcc. ----
3163 if (isParsingIntelSyntax() && 0
3164 (PatchedName == "jmp" || PatchedName == "jc" || PatchedName == "jnc" || 0
3165 PatchedName == "jcxz" || PatchedName == "jecxz" || 0
3166 (PatchedName.startswith("j") && 0
3167 ParseConditionCode(PatchedName.substr(1)) != X86::COND_INVALID))) { 0
3168 StringRef NextTok = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3169 if (Parser.isParsingMasm() ? NextTok.equals_insensitive("short") 0
3170 : NextTok == "short") { 0
3171 SMLoc NameEndLoc = ----
3172 NameLoc.getFromPointer(NameLoc.getPointer() + Name.size()); 0
3173 // Eat the short keyword. ----
3174 Parser.Lex(); 0
3175 // MS and GAS ignore the short keyword; they both determine the jmp type ----
3176 // based on the distance of the label. (NASM does emit different code with ----
3177 // and without "short," though.) ----
3178 InstInfo->AsmRewrites->emplace_back(AOK_Skip, NameEndLoc, 0
3179 NextTok.size() + 1); 0
3180 } ----
3181 } ----
3182 ----
3183 // FIXME: Hack to recognize setneb as setne. ----
3184 if (PatchedName.startswith("set") && PatchedName.endswith("b") && 0
3185 PatchedName != "setb" && PatchedName != "setnb") 0
3186 PatchedName = PatchedName.substr(0, Name.size()-1); 0
3187 ----
3188 unsigned ComparisonPredicate = ~0U; 0
3189 ----
3190 // FIXME: Hack to recognize cmp{sh,ss,sd,ph,ps,pd}. ----
3191 if ((PatchedName.startswith("cmp") || PatchedName.startswith("vcmp")) && 0
3192 (PatchedName.endswith("ss") || PatchedName.endswith("sd") || 0
3193 PatchedName.endswith("sh") || PatchedName.endswith("ph") || 0
3194 PatchedName.endswith("ps") || PatchedName.endswith("pd"))) { 0
3195 bool IsVCMP = PatchedName[0] == 'v'; 0
3196 unsigned CCIdx = IsVCMP ? 4 : 3; 0
3197 unsigned CC = StringSwitch( 0
3198 PatchedName.slice(CCIdx, PatchedName.size() - 2)) 0
3199 .Case("eq", 0x00) 0
3200 .Case("eq_oq", 0x00) 0
3201 .Case("lt", 0x01) 0
3202 .Case("lt_os", 0x01) 0
3203 .Case("le", 0x02) 0
3204 .Case("le_os", 0x02) 0
3205 .Case("unord", 0x03) 0
3206 .Case("unord_q", 0x03) 0
3207 .Case("neq", 0x04) 0
3208 .Case("neq_uq", 0x04) 0
3209 .Case("nlt", 0x05) 0
3210 .Case("nlt_us", 0x05) 0
3211 .Case("nle", 0x06) 0
3212 .Case("nle_us", 0x06) 0
3213 .Case("ord", 0x07) 0
3214 .Case("ord_q", 0x07) 0
3215 /* AVX only from here */ ----
3216 .Case("eq_uq", 0x08) 0
3217 .Case("nge", 0x09) 0
3218 .Case("nge_us", 0x09) 0
3219 .Case("ngt", 0x0A) 0
3220 .Case("ngt_us", 0x0A) 0
3221 .Case("false", 0x0B) 0
3222 .Case("false_oq", 0x0B) 0
3223 .Case("neq_oq", 0x0C) 0
3224 .Case("ge", 0x0D) 0
3225 .Case("ge_os", 0x0D) 0
3226 .Case("gt", 0x0E) 0
3227 .Case("gt_os", 0x0E) 0
3228 .Case("true", 0x0F) 0
3229 .Case("true_uq", 0x0F) 0
3230 .Case("eq_os", 0x10) 0
3231 .Case("lt_oq", 0x11) 0
3232 .Case("le_oq", 0x12) 0
3233 .Case("unord_s", 0x13) 0
3234 .Case("neq_us", 0x14) 0
3235 .Case("nlt_uq", 0x15) 0
3236 .Case("nle_uq", 0x16) 0
3237 .Case("ord_s", 0x17) 0
3238 .Case("eq_us", 0x18) 0
3239 .Case("nge_uq", 0x19) 0
3240 .Case("ngt_uq", 0x1A) 0
3241 .Case("false_os", 0x1B) 0
3242 .Case("neq_os", 0x1C) 0
3243 .Case("ge_oq", 0x1D) 0
3244 .Case("gt_oq", 0x1E) 0
3245 .Case("true_us", 0x1F) 0
3246 .Default(~0U); 0
3247 if (CC != ~0U && (IsVCMP || CC < 8) && 0
3248 (IsVCMP || PatchedName.back() != 'h')) { 0
3249 if (PatchedName.endswith("ss")) 0
3250 PatchedName = IsVCMP ? "vcmpss" : "cmpss"; 0
3251 else if (PatchedName.endswith("sd")) 0
3252 PatchedName = IsVCMP ? "vcmpsd" : "cmpsd"; 0
3253 else if (PatchedName.endswith("ps")) 0
3254 PatchedName = IsVCMP ? "vcmpps" : "cmpps"; 0
3255 else if (PatchedName.endswith("pd")) 0
3256 PatchedName = IsVCMP ? "vcmppd" : "cmppd"; 0
3257 else if (PatchedName.endswith("sh")) 0
3258 PatchedName = "vcmpsh"; 0
3259 else if (PatchedName.endswith("ph")) 0
3260 PatchedName = "vcmpph"; 0
3261 else ----
3262 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected suffix!"); 0
3263 ----
3264 ComparisonPredicate = CC; 0
3265 } ----
3266 } ----
3267 ----
3268 // FIXME: Hack to recognize vpcmp{ub,uw,ud,uq,b,w,d,q}. ----
3269 if (PatchedName.startswith("vpcmp") && 0
3270 (PatchedName.back() == 'b' || PatchedName.back() == 'w' || 0
3271 PatchedName.back() == 'd' || PatchedName.back() == 'q')) { 0
3272 unsigned SuffixSize = PatchedName.drop_back().back() == 'u' ? 2 : 1; 0
3273 unsigned CC = StringSwitch( 0
3274 PatchedName.slice(5, PatchedName.size() - SuffixSize)) 0
3275 .Case("eq", 0x0) // Only allowed on unsigned. Checked below. 0
3276 .Case("lt", 0x1) 0
3277 .Case("le", 0x2) 0
3278 //.Case("false", 0x3) // Not a documented alias. ----
3279 .Case("neq", 0x4) 0
3280 .Case("nlt", 0x5) 0
3281 .Case("nle", 0x6) 0
3282 //.Case("true", 0x7) // Not a documented alias. ----
3283 .Default(~0U); 0
3284 if (CC != ~0U && (CC != 0 || SuffixSize == 2)) { 0
3285 switch (PatchedName.back()) { 0
3286 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected character!"); 0
3287 case 'b': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcmpub" : "vpcmpb"; break; 0
3288 case 'w': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcmpuw" : "vpcmpw"; break; 0
3289 case 'd': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcmpud" : "vpcmpd"; break; 0
3290 case 'q': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcmpuq" : "vpcmpq"; break; 0
3291 } ----
3292 // Set up the immediate to push into the operands later. ----
3293 ComparisonPredicate = CC; 0
3294 } ----
3295 } ----
3296 ----
3297 // FIXME: Hack to recognize vpcom{ub,uw,ud,uq,b,w,d,q}. ----
3298 if (PatchedName.startswith("vpcom") && 0
3299 (PatchedName.back() == 'b' || PatchedName.back() == 'w' || 0
3300 PatchedName.back() == 'd' || PatchedName.back() == 'q')) { 0
3301 unsigned SuffixSize = PatchedName.drop_back().back() == 'u' ? 2 : 1; 0
3302 unsigned CC = StringSwitch( 0
3303 PatchedName.slice(5, PatchedName.size() - SuffixSize)) 0
3304 .Case("lt", 0x0) 0
3305 .Case("le", 0x1) 0
3306 .Case("gt", 0x2) 0
3307 .Case("ge", 0x3) 0
3308 .Case("eq", 0x4) 0
3309 .Case("neq", 0x5) 0
3310 .Case("false", 0x6) 0
3311 .Case("true", 0x7) 0
3312 .Default(~0U); 0
3313 if (CC != ~0U) { 0
3314 switch (PatchedName.back()) { 0
3315 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected character!"); 0
3316 case 'b': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcomub" : "vpcomb"; break; 0
3317 case 'w': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcomuw" : "vpcomw"; break; 0
3318 case 'd': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcomud" : "vpcomd"; break; 0
3319 case 'q': PatchedName = SuffixSize == 2 ? "vpcomuq" : "vpcomq"; break; 0
3320 } ----
3321 // Set up the immediate to push into the operands later. ----
3322 ComparisonPredicate = CC; 0
3323 } ----
3324 } ----
3325 ----
3326 ----
3327 // Determine whether this is an instruction prefix. ----
3328 // FIXME: ----
3329 // Enhance prefixes integrity robustness. for example, following forms ----
3330 // are currently tolerated: ----
3331 // repz repnz ; GAS errors for the use of two similar prefixes ----
3332 // lock addq %rax, %rbx ; Destination operand must be of memory type ----
3333 // xacquire ; xacquire must be accompanied by 'lock' ----
3334 bool IsPrefix = ----
3335 StringSwitch(Name) 0
3336 .Cases("cs", "ds", "es", "fs", "gs", "ss", true) 0
3337 .Cases("rex64", "data32", "data16", "addr32", "addr16", true) 0
3338 .Cases("xacquire", "xrelease", true) 0
3339 .Cases("acquire", "release", isParsingIntelSyntax()) 0
3340 .Default(false); 0
3341 ----
3342 auto isLockRepeatNtPrefix = [](StringRef N) { 0
3343 return StringSwitch(N) 0
3344 .Cases("lock", "rep", "repe", "repz", "repne", "repnz", "notrack", true) 0
3345 .Default(false); 0
3346 }; ----
3347 ----
3348 bool CurlyAsEndOfStatement = false; 0
3349 ----
3350 unsigned Flags = X86::IP_NO_PREFIX; 0
3351 while (isLockRepeatNtPrefix(Name.lower())) { 0
3352 unsigned Prefix = ----
3353 StringSwitch(Name) 0
3354 .Cases("lock", "lock", X86::IP_HAS_LOCK) 0
3355 .Cases("rep", "repe", "repz", X86::IP_HAS_REPEAT) 0
3356 .Cases("repne", "repnz", X86::IP_HAS_REPEAT_NE) 0
3357 .Cases("notrack", "notrack", X86::IP_HAS_NOTRACK) 0
3358 .Default(X86::IP_NO_PREFIX); // Invalid prefix (impossible) 0
3359 Flags |= Prefix; 0
3360 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
3361 // We don't have real instr with the given prefix ----
3362 // let's use the prefix as the instr. ----
3363 // TODO: there could be several prefixes one after another ----
3364 Flags = X86::IP_NO_PREFIX; 0
3365 break; 0
3366 } ----
3367 // FIXME: The mnemonic won't match correctly if its not in lower case. ----
3368 Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3369 Parser.Lex(); // eat the prefix 0
3370 // Hack: we could have something like "rep # some comment" or ----
3371 // "lock; cmpxchg16b $1" or "lock\0A\09incl" or "lock/incl" ----
3372 while (Name.startswith(";") || Name.startswith("\n") || 0
3373 Name.startswith("#") || Name.startswith("\t") || 0
3374 Name.startswith("/")) { 0
3375 // FIXME: The mnemonic won't match correctly if its not in lower case. ----
3376 Name = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3377 Parser.Lex(); // go to next prefix or instr 0
3378 } ----
3379 } ----
3380 ----
3381 if (Flags) 0
3382 PatchedName = Name; 0
3383 ----
3384 // Hacks to handle 'data16' and 'data32' ----
3385 if (PatchedName == "data16" && is16BitMode()) { 0
3386 return Error(NameLoc, "redundant data16 prefix"); 0
3387 } ----
3388 if (PatchedName == "data32") { 0
3389 if (is32BitMode()) 0
3390 return Error(NameLoc, "redundant data32 prefix"); 0
3391 if (is64BitMode()) 0
3392 return Error(NameLoc, "'data32' is not supported in 64-bit mode"); 0
3393 // Hack to 'data16' for the table lookup. ----
3394 PatchedName = "data16"; 0
3395 ----
3396 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
3397 StringRef Next = Parser.getTok().getString(); 0
3398 getLexer().Lex(); 0
3399 // data32 effectively changes the instruction suffix. ----
3400 // TODO Generalize. ----
3401 if (Next == "callw") 0
3402 Next = "calll"; 0
3403 if (Next == "ljmpw") 0
3404 Next = "ljmpl"; 0
3405 ----
3406 Name = Next; 0
3407 PatchedName = Name; 0
3408 ForcedDataPrefix = X86::Is32Bit; 0
3409 IsPrefix = false; 0
3410 } ----
3411 } ----
3412 ----
3413 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateToken(PatchedName, NameLoc)); 0
3414 ----
3415 // Push the immediate if we extracted one from the mnemonic. ----
3416 if (ComparisonPredicate != ~0U && !isParsingIntelSyntax()) { 0
3417 const MCExpr *ImmOp = MCConstantExpr::create(ComparisonPredicate, 0
3418 getParser().getContext()); 0
3419 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateImm(ImmOp, NameLoc, NameLoc)); 0
3420 } ----
3421 ----
3422 // This does the actual operand parsing. Don't parse any more if we have a ----
3423 // prefix juxtaposed with an operation like "lock incl 4(%rax)", because we ----
3424 // just want to parse the "lock" as the first instruction and the "incl" as ----
3425 // the next one. ----
3426 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement) && !IsPrefix) { 0
3427 // Parse '*' modifier. ----
3428 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Star)) 0
3429 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateToken("*", consumeToken())); 0
3430 ----
3431 // Read the operands. ----
3432 while (true) { ----
3433 if (parseOperand(Operands, Name)) 0
3434 return true; 0
3435 if (HandleAVX512Operand(Operands)) 0
3436 return true; 0
3437 ----
3438 // check for comma and eat it ----
3439 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::Comma)) 0
3440 Parser.Lex(); 0
3441 else ----
3442 break; 0
3443 } ----
3444 ----
3445 // In MS inline asm curly braces mark the beginning/end of a block, ----
3446 // therefore they should be interepreted as end of statement ----
3447 CurlyAsEndOfStatement = 0
3448 isParsingIntelSyntax() && isParsingMSInlineAsm() && 0
3449 (getLexer().is(AsmToken::LCurly) || getLexer().is(AsmToken::RCurly)); 0
3450 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement) && !CurlyAsEndOfStatement) 0
3451 return TokError("unexpected token in argument list"); 0
3452 } ----
3453 ----
3454 // Push the immediate if we extracted one from the mnemonic. ----
3455 if (ComparisonPredicate != ~0U && isParsingIntelSyntax()) { 0
3456 const MCExpr *ImmOp = MCConstantExpr::create(ComparisonPredicate, 0
3457 getParser().getContext()); 0
3458 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreateImm(ImmOp, NameLoc, NameLoc)); 0
3459 } ----
3460 ----
3461 // Consume the EndOfStatement or the prefix separator Slash ----
3462 if (getLexer().is(AsmToken::EndOfStatement) || 0
3463 (IsPrefix && getLexer().is(AsmToken::Slash))) 0
3464 Parser.Lex(); 0
3465 else if (CurlyAsEndOfStatement) 0
3466 // Add an actual EndOfStatement before the curly brace ----
3467 Info.AsmRewrites->emplace_back(AOK_EndOfStatement, 0
3468 getLexer().getTok().getLoc(), 0); 0
3469 ----
3470 // This is for gas compatibility and cannot be done in td. ----
3471 // Adding "p" for some floating point with no argument. ----
3472 // For example: fsub --> fsubp ----
3473 bool IsFp = ----
3474 Name == "fsub" || Name == "fdiv" || Name == "fsubr" || Name == "fdivr"; 0
3475 if (IsFp && Operands.size() == 1) { 0
3476 const char *Repl = StringSwitch(Name) 0
3477 .Case("fsub", "fsubp") 0
3478 .Case("fdiv", "fdivp") 0
3479 .Case("fsubr", "fsubrp") 0
3480 .Case("fdivr", "fdivrp"); 0
3481 static_cast(*Operands[0]).setTokenValue(Repl); 0
3482 } ----
3483 ----
3484 if ((Name == "mov" || Name == "movw" || Name == "movl") && 0
3485 (Operands.size() == 3)) { 0
3486 X86Operand &Op1 = (X86Operand &)*Operands[1]; 0
3487 X86Operand &Op2 = (X86Operand &)*Operands[2]; 0
3488 SMLoc Loc = Op1.getEndLoc(); 0
3489 // Moving a 32 or 16 bit value into a segment register has the same ----
3490 // behavior. Modify such instructions to always take shorter form. ----
3491 if (Op1.isReg() && Op2.isReg() && 0
3492 X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::SEGMENT_REGRegClassID].contains( 0
3493 Op2.getReg()) && 0
3494 (X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::GR16RegClassID].contains(Op1.getReg()) || 0
3495 X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::GR32RegClassID].contains(Op1.getReg()))) { 0
3496 // Change instruction name to match new instruction. ----
3497 if (Name != "mov" && Name[3] == (is16BitMode() ? 'l' : 'w')) { 0
3498 Name = is16BitMode() ? "movw" : "movl"; 0
3499 Operands[0] = X86Operand::CreateToken(Name, NameLoc); 0
3500 } ----
3501 // Select the correct equivalent 16-/32-bit source register. ----
3502 MCRegister Reg = ----
3503 getX86SubSuperRegister(Op1.getReg(), is16BitMode() ? 16 : 32); 0
3504 Operands[1] = X86Operand::CreateReg(Reg, Loc, Loc); 0
3505 } ----
3506 } ----
3507 ----
3508 // This is a terrible hack to handle "out[s]?[bwl]? %al, (%dx)" -> ----
3509 // "outb %al, %dx". Out doesn't take a memory form, but this is a widely ----
3510 // documented form in various unofficial manuals, so a lot of code uses it. ----
3511 if ((Name == "outb" || Name == "outsb" || Name == "outw" || Name == "outsw" || 0
3512 Name == "outl" || Name == "outsl" || Name == "out" || Name == "outs") && 0
3513 Operands.size() == 3) { 0
3514 X86Operand &Op = (X86Operand &)*Operands.back(); 0
3515 if (Op.isDXReg()) 0
3516 Operands.back() = X86Operand::CreateReg(X86::DX, Op.getStartLoc(), 0
3517 Op.getEndLoc()); 0
3518 } ----
3519 // Same hack for "in[s]?[bwl]? (%dx), %al" -> "inb %dx, %al". ----
3520 if ((Name == "inb" || Name == "insb" || Name == "inw" || Name == "insw" || 0
3521 Name == "inl" || Name == "insl" || Name == "in" || Name == "ins") && 0
3522 Operands.size() == 3) { 0
3523 X86Operand &Op = (X86Operand &)*Operands[1]; 0
3524 if (Op.isDXReg()) 0
3525 Operands[1] = X86Operand::CreateReg(X86::DX, Op.getStartLoc(), 0
3526 Op.getEndLoc()); 0
3527 } ----
3528 ----
3529 SmallVector, 2> TmpOperands; 0
3530 bool HadVerifyError = false; 0
3531 ----
3532 // Append default arguments to "ins[bwld]" ----
3533 if (Name.startswith("ins") && 0
3534 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 3) && 0
3535 (Name == "insb" || Name == "insw" || Name == "insl" || Name == "insd" || 0
3536 Name == "ins")) { 0
3537 ----
3538 AddDefaultSrcDestOperands(TmpOperands, 0
3539 X86Operand::CreateReg(X86::DX, NameLoc, NameLoc), 0
3540 DefaultMemDIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3541 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3542 } ----
3543 ----
3544 // Append default arguments to "outs[bwld]" ----
3545 if (Name.startswith("outs") && 0
3546 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 3) && 0
3547 (Name == "outsb" || Name == "outsw" || Name == "outsl" || 0
3548 Name == "outsd" || Name == "outs")) { 0
3549 AddDefaultSrcDestOperands(TmpOperands, DefaultMemSIOperand(NameLoc), 0
3550 X86Operand::CreateReg(X86::DX, NameLoc, NameLoc)); 0
3551 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3552 } ----
3553 ----
3554 // Transform "lods[bwlq]" into "lods[bwlq] ($SIREG)" for appropriate ----
3555 // values of $SIREG according to the mode. It would be nice if this ----
3556 // could be achieved with InstAlias in the tables. ----
3557 if (Name.startswith("lods") && 0
3558 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 2) && 0
3559 (Name == "lods" || Name == "lodsb" || Name == "lodsw" || 0
3560 Name == "lodsl" || Name == "lodsd" || Name == "lodsq")) { 0
3561 TmpOperands.push_back(DefaultMemSIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3562 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3563 } ----
3564 ----
3565 // Transform "stos[bwlq]" into "stos[bwlq] ($DIREG)" for appropriate ----
3566 // values of $DIREG according to the mode. It would be nice if this ----
3567 // could be achieved with InstAlias in the tables. ----
3568 if (Name.startswith("stos") && 0
3569 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 2) && 0
3570 (Name == "stos" || Name == "stosb" || Name == "stosw" || 0
3571 Name == "stosl" || Name == "stosd" || Name == "stosq")) { 0
3572 TmpOperands.push_back(DefaultMemDIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3573 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3574 } ----
3575 ----
3576 // Transform "scas[bwlq]" into "scas[bwlq] ($DIREG)" for appropriate ----
3577 // values of $DIREG according to the mode. It would be nice if this ----
3578 // could be achieved with InstAlias in the tables. ----
3579 if (Name.startswith("scas") && 0
3580 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 2) && 0
3581 (Name == "scas" || Name == "scasb" || Name == "scasw" || 0
3582 Name == "scasl" || Name == "scasd" || Name == "scasq")) { 0
3583 TmpOperands.push_back(DefaultMemDIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3584 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3585 } ----
3586 ----
3587 // Add default SI and DI operands to "cmps[bwlq]". ----
3588 if (Name.startswith("cmps") && 0
3589 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 3) && 0
3590 (Name == "cmps" || Name == "cmpsb" || Name == "cmpsw" || 0
3591 Name == "cmpsl" || Name == "cmpsd" || Name == "cmpsq")) { 0
3592 AddDefaultSrcDestOperands(TmpOperands, DefaultMemDIOperand(NameLoc), 0
3593 DefaultMemSIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3594 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3595 } ----
3596 ----
3597 // Add default SI and DI operands to "movs[bwlq]". ----
3598 if (((Name.startswith("movs") && 0
3599 (Name == "movs" || Name == "movsb" || Name == "movsw" || 0
3600 Name == "movsl" || Name == "movsd" || Name == "movsq")) || 0
3601 (Name.startswith("smov") && 0
3602 (Name == "smov" || Name == "smovb" || Name == "smovw" || 0
3603 Name == "smovl" || Name == "smovd" || Name == "smovq"))) && 0
3604 (Operands.size() == 1 || Operands.size() == 3)) { 0
3605 if (Name == "movsd" && Operands.size() == 1 && !isParsingIntelSyntax()) 0
3606 Operands.back() = X86Operand::CreateToken("movsl", NameLoc); 0
3607 AddDefaultSrcDestOperands(TmpOperands, DefaultMemSIOperand(NameLoc), 0
3608 DefaultMemDIOperand(NameLoc)); 0
3609 HadVerifyError = VerifyAndAdjustOperands(Operands, TmpOperands); 0
3610 } ----
3611 ----
3612 // Check if we encountered an error for one the string insturctions ----
3613 if (HadVerifyError) { 0
3614 return HadVerifyError; 0
3615 } ----
3616 ----
3617 // Transforms "xlat mem8" into "xlatb" ----
3618 if ((Name == "xlat" || Name == "xlatb") && Operands.size() == 2) { 0
3619 X86Operand &Op1 = static_cast(*Operands[1]); 0
3620 if (Op1.isMem8()) { 0
3621 Warning(Op1.getStartLoc(), "memory operand is only for determining the " 0
3622 "size, (R|E)BX will be used for the location"); ----
3623 Operands.pop_back(); 0
3624 static_cast(*Operands[0]).setTokenValue("xlatb"); 0
3625 } ----
3626 } ----
3627 ----
3628 if (Flags) 0
3629 Operands.push_back(X86Operand::CreatePrefix(Flags, NameLoc, NameLoc)); 0
3630 return false; 0
3631 } ----
3632 ----
3633 bool X86AsmParser::processInstruction(MCInst &Inst, const OperandVector &Ops) { 0
3634 if (ForcedVEXEncoding != VEXEncoding_VEX3 && 0
3635 X86::optimizeInstFromVEX3ToVEX2(Inst, MII.get(Inst.getOpcode()))) 0
3636 return true; 0
3637 ----
3638 if (X86::optimizeShiftRotateWithImmediateOne(Inst)) 0
3639 return true; 0
3640 ----
3641 switch (Inst.getOpcode()) { 0
3642 default: return false; 0
3643 case X86::JMP_1: 0
3644 // {disp32} forces a larger displacement as if the instruction was relaxed. ----
3645 // NOTE: 16-bit mode uses 16-bit displacement even though it says {disp32}. ----
3646 // This matches GNU assembler. ----
3647 if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp32) { 0
3648 Inst.setOpcode(is16BitMode() ? X86::JMP_2 : X86::JMP_4); 0
3649 return true; 0
3650 } ----
3651 ----
3652 return false; 0
3653 case X86::JCC_1: 0
3654 // {disp32} forces a larger displacement as if the instruction was relaxed. ----
3655 // NOTE: 16-bit mode uses 16-bit displacement even though it says {disp32}. ----
3656 // This matches GNU assembler. ----
3657 if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp32) { 0
3658 Inst.setOpcode(is16BitMode() ? X86::JCC_2 : X86::JCC_4); 0
3659 return true; 0
3660 } ----
3661 ----
3662 return false; 0
3663 case X86::INT: { 0
3664 // Transforms "int $3" into "int3" as a size optimization. ----
3665 // We can't write this as an InstAlias. ----
3666 if (!Inst.getOperand(0).isImm() || Inst.getOperand(0).getImm() != 3) 0
3667 return false; 0
3668 Inst.clear(); 0
3669 Inst.setOpcode(X86::INT3); 0
3670 return true; 0
3671 } ----
3672 } ----
3673 } ----
3674 ----
3675 bool X86AsmParser::validateInstruction(MCInst &Inst, const OperandVector &Ops) { 0
3676 using namespace X86; ----
3677 const MCRegisterInfo *MRI = getContext().getRegisterInfo(); 0
3678 unsigned Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
3679 uint64_t TSFlags = MII.get(Opcode).TSFlags; 0
3680 if (isVFCMADDCPH(Opcode) || isVFCMADDCSH(Opcode) || isVFMADDCPH(Opcode) || 0
3681 isVFMADDCSH(Opcode)) { 0
3682 unsigned Dest = Inst.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
3683 for (unsigned i = 2; i < Inst.getNumOperands(); i++) 0
3684 if (Inst.getOperand(i).isReg() && Dest == Inst.getOperand(i).getReg()) 0
3685 return Warning(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), "Destination register should be " 0
3686 "distinct from source registers"); 0
3687 } else if (isVFCMULCPH(Opcode) || isVFCMULCSH(Opcode) || isVFMULCPH(Opcode) || 0
3688 isVFMULCSH(Opcode)) { 0
3689 unsigned Dest = Inst.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
3690 // The mask variants have different operand list. Scan from the third ----
3691 // operand to avoid emitting incorrect warning. ----
3692 // VFMULCPHZrr Dest, Src1, Src2 ----
3693 // VFMULCPHZrrk Dest, Dest, Mask, Src1, Src2 ----
3694 // VFMULCPHZrrkz Dest, Mask, Src1, Src2 ----
3695 for (unsigned i = TSFlags & X86II::EVEX_K ? 2 : 1; 0
3696 i < Inst.getNumOperands(); i++) 0
3697 if (Inst.getOperand(i).isReg() && Dest == Inst.getOperand(i).getReg()) 0
3698 return Warning(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), "Destination register should be " 0
3699 "distinct from source registers"); 0
3700 } else if (isV4FMADDPS(Opcode) || isV4FMADDSS(Opcode) || 0
3701 isV4FNMADDPS(Opcode) || isV4FNMADDSS(Opcode) || 0
3702 isVP4DPWSSDS(Opcode) || isVP4DPWSSD(Opcode)) { 0
3703 unsigned Src2 = Inst.getOperand(Inst.getNumOperands() - 0
3704 X86::AddrNumOperands - 1).getReg(); 0
3705 unsigned Src2Enc = MRI->getEncodingValue(Src2); 0
3706 if (Src2Enc % 4 != 0) { 0
3707 StringRef RegName = X86IntelInstPrinter::getRegisterName(Src2); 0
3708 unsigned GroupStart = (Src2Enc / 4) * 4; 0
3709 unsigned GroupEnd = GroupStart + 3; 0
3710 return Warning(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), 0
3711 "source register '" + RegName + "' implicitly denotes '" + 0
3712 RegName.take_front(3) + Twine(GroupStart) + "' to '" + 0
3713 RegName.take_front(3) + Twine(GroupEnd) + 0
3714 "' source group"); 0
3715 } ----
3716 } else if (isVGATHERDPD(Opcode) || isVGATHERDPS(Opcode) || 0
3717 isVGATHERQPD(Opcode) || isVGATHERQPS(Opcode) || 0
3718 isVPGATHERDD(Opcode) || isVPGATHERDQ(Opcode) || 0
3719 isVPGATHERQD(Opcode) || isVPGATHERQQ(Opcode)) { 0
3720 bool HasEVEX = (TSFlags & X86II::EncodingMask) == X86II::EVEX; 0
3721 if (HasEVEX) { 0
3722 unsigned Dest = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(0).getReg()); 0
3723 unsigned Index = MRI->getEncodingValue( 0
3724 Inst.getOperand(4 + X86::AddrIndexReg).getReg()); 0
3725 if (Dest == Index) 0
3726 return Warning(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), "index and destination registers " 0
3727 "should be distinct"); 0
3728 } else { ----
3729 unsigned Dest = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(0).getReg()); 0
3730 unsigned Mask = MRI->getEncodingValue(Inst.getOperand(1).getReg()); 0
3731 unsigned Index = MRI->getEncodingValue( 0
3732 Inst.getOperand(3 + X86::AddrIndexReg).getReg()); 0
3733 if (Dest == Mask || Dest == Index || Mask == Index) 0
3734 return Warning(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), "mask, index, and destination " 0
3735 "registers should be distinct"); 0
3736 } ----
3737 } ----
3738 ----
3739 // Check that we aren't mixing AH/BH/CH/DH with REX prefix. We only need to ----
3740 // check this with the legacy encoding, VEX/EVEX/XOP don't use REX. ----
3741 if ((TSFlags & X86II::EncodingMask) == 0) { 0
3742 MCPhysReg HReg = X86::NoRegister; 0
3743 bool UsesRex = TSFlags & X86II::REX_W; 0
3744 unsigned NumOps = Inst.getNumOperands(); 0
3745 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumOps; ++i) { 0
3746 const MCOperand &MO = Inst.getOperand(i); 0
3747 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
3748 continue; 0
3749 unsigned Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
3750 if (Reg == X86::AH || Reg == X86::BH || Reg == X86::CH || Reg == X86::DH) 0
3751 HReg = Reg; 0
3752 if (X86II::isX86_64NonExtLowByteReg(Reg) || 0
3753 X86II::isX86_64ExtendedReg(Reg)) 0
3754 UsesRex = true; 0
3755 } ----
3756 ----
3757 if (UsesRex && HReg != X86::NoRegister) { 0
3758 StringRef RegName = X86IntelInstPrinter::getRegisterName(HReg); 0
3759 return Error(Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), 0
3760 "can't encode '" + RegName + "' in an instruction requiring " 0
3761 "REX prefix"); 0
3762 } ----
3763 } ----
3764 ----
3765 if ((Opcode == X86::PREFETCHIT0 || Opcode == X86::PREFETCHIT1)) { 0
3766 const MCOperand &MO = Inst.getOperand(X86::AddrBaseReg); 0
3767 if (!MO.isReg() || MO.getReg() != X86::RIP) 0
3768 return Warning( 0
3769 Ops[0]->getStartLoc(), 0
3770 Twine((Inst.getOpcode() == X86::PREFETCHIT0 ? "'prefetchit0'" 0
3771 : "'prefetchit1'")) + 0
3772 " only supports RIP-relative address"); 0
3773 } ----
3774 return false; 0
3775 } ----
3776 ----
3777 void X86AsmParser::emitWarningForSpecialLVIInstruction(SMLoc Loc) { 0
3778 Warning(Loc, "Instruction may be vulnerable to LVI and " 0
3779 "requires manual mitigation"); ----
3780 Note(SMLoc(), "See https://software.intel.com/" 0
3781 "security-software-guidance/insights/" ----
3782 "deep-dive-load-value-injection#specialinstructions" ----
3783 " for more information"); ----
3784 } 0
3785 ----
3786 /// RET instructions and also instructions that indirect calls/jumps from memory ----
3787 /// combine a load and a branch within a single instruction. To mitigate these ----
3788 /// instructions against LVI, they must be decomposed into separate load and ----
3789 /// branch instructions, with an LFENCE in between. For more details, see: ----
3790 /// - X86LoadValueInjectionRetHardening.cpp ----
3791 /// - X86LoadValueInjectionIndirectThunks.cpp ----
3792 /// - https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/insights/deep-dive-load-value-injection ----
3793 /// ----
3794 /// Returns `true` if a mitigation was applied or warning was emitted. ----
3795 void X86AsmParser::applyLVICFIMitigation(MCInst &Inst, MCStreamer &Out) { 0
3796 // Information on control-flow instructions that require manual mitigation can ----
3797 // be found here: ----
3798 // https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/insights/deep-dive-load-value-injection#specialinstructions ----
3799 switch (Inst.getOpcode()) { 0
3800 case X86::RET16: 0
3801 case X86::RET32: ----
3802 case X86::RET64: ----
3803 case X86::RETI16: ----
3804 case X86::RETI32: ----
3805 case X86::RETI64: { ----
3806 MCInst ShlInst, FenceInst; 0
3807 bool Parse32 = is32BitMode() || Code16GCC; 0
3808 unsigned Basereg = ----
3809 is64BitMode() ? X86::RSP : (Parse32 ? X86::ESP : X86::SP); 0
3810 const MCExpr *Disp = MCConstantExpr::create(0, getContext()); 0
3811 auto ShlMemOp = X86Operand::CreateMem(getPointerWidth(), /*SegReg=*/0, Disp, 0
3812 /*BaseReg=*/Basereg, /*IndexReg=*/0, ----
3813 /*Scale=*/1, SMLoc{}, SMLoc{}, 0); 0
3814 ShlInst.setOpcode(X86::SHL64mi); 0
3815 ShlMemOp->addMemOperands(ShlInst, 5); 0
3816 ShlInst.addOperand(MCOperand::createImm(0)); 0
3817 FenceInst.setOpcode(X86::LFENCE); 0
3818 Out.emitInstruction(ShlInst, getSTI()); 0
3819 Out.emitInstruction(FenceInst, getSTI()); 0
3820 return; 0
3821 } 0
3822 case X86::JMP16m: 0
3823 case X86::JMP32m: ----
3824 case X86::JMP64m: ----
3825 case X86::CALL16m: ----
3826 case X86::CALL32m: ----
3827 case X86::CALL64m: ----
3828 emitWarningForSpecialLVIInstruction(Inst.getLoc()); 0
3829 return; 0
3830 } ----
3831 } ----
3832 ----
3833 /// To mitigate LVI, every instruction that performs a load can be followed by ----
3834 /// an LFENCE instruction to squash any potential mis-speculation. There are ----
3835 /// some instructions that require additional considerations, and may requre ----
3836 /// manual mitigation. For more details, see: ----
3837 /// https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/insights/deep-dive-load-value-injection ----
3838 /// ----
3839 /// Returns `true` if a mitigation was applied or warning was emitted. ----
3840 void X86AsmParser::applyLVILoadHardeningMitigation(MCInst &Inst, 0
3841 MCStreamer &Out) { ----
3842 auto Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
3843 auto Flags = Inst.getFlags(); 0
3844 if ((Flags & X86::IP_HAS_REPEAT) || (Flags & X86::IP_HAS_REPEAT_NE)) { 0
3845 // Information on REP string instructions that require manual mitigation can ----
3846 // be found here: ----
3847 // https://software.intel.com/security-software-guidance/insights/deep-dive-load-value-injection#specialinstructions ----
3848 switch (Opcode) { 0
3849 case X86::CMPSB: 0
3850 case X86::CMPSW: ----
3851 case X86::CMPSL: ----
3852 case X86::CMPSQ: ----
3853 case X86::SCASB: ----
3854 case X86::SCASW: ----
3855 case X86::SCASL: ----
3856 case X86::SCASQ: ----
3857 emitWarningForSpecialLVIInstruction(Inst.getLoc()); 0
3858 return; 0
3859 } ----
3860 } else if (Opcode == X86::REP_PREFIX || Opcode == X86::REPNE_PREFIX) { 0
3861 // If a REP instruction is found on its own line, it may or may not be ----
3862 // followed by a vulnerable instruction. Emit a warning just in case. ----
3863 emitWarningForSpecialLVIInstruction(Inst.getLoc()); 0
3864 return; 0
3865 } ----
3866 ----
3867 const MCInstrDesc &MCID = MII.get(Inst.getOpcode()); 0
3868 ----
3869 // Can't mitigate after terminators or calls. A control flow change may have ----
3870 // already occurred. ----
3871 if (MCID.isTerminator() || MCID.isCall()) 0
3872 return; 0
3873 ----
3874 // LFENCE has the mayLoad property, don't double fence. ----
3875 if (MCID.mayLoad() && Inst.getOpcode() != X86::LFENCE) { 0
3876 MCInst FenceInst; 0
3877 FenceInst.setOpcode(X86::LFENCE); 0
3878 Out.emitInstruction(FenceInst, getSTI()); 0
3879 } 0
3880 } ----
3881 ----
3882 void X86AsmParser::emitInstruction(MCInst &Inst, OperandVector &Operands, 0
3883 MCStreamer &Out) { ----
3884 if (LVIInlineAsmHardening && 0
3885 getSTI().hasFeature(X86::FeatureLVIControlFlowIntegrity)) 0
3886 applyLVICFIMitigation(Inst, Out); 0
3887 ----
3888 Out.emitInstruction(Inst, getSTI()); 0
3889 ----
3890 if (LVIInlineAsmHardening && 0
3891 getSTI().hasFeature(X86::FeatureLVILoadHardening)) 0
3892 applyLVILoadHardeningMitigation(Inst, Out); 0
3893 } 0
3894 ----
3895 bool X86AsmParser::MatchAndEmitInstruction(SMLoc IDLoc, unsigned &Opcode, 0
3896 OperandVector &Operands, ----
3897 MCStreamer &Out, uint64_t &ErrorInfo, ----
3898 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
3899 if (isParsingIntelSyntax()) 0
3900 return MatchAndEmitIntelInstruction(IDLoc, Opcode, Operands, Out, ErrorInfo, 0
3901 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
3902 return MatchAndEmitATTInstruction(IDLoc, Opcode, Operands, Out, ErrorInfo, 0
3903 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
3904 } ----
3905 ----
3906 void X86AsmParser::MatchFPUWaitAlias(SMLoc IDLoc, X86Operand &Op, 0
3907 OperandVector &Operands, MCStreamer &Out, ----
3908 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
3909 // FIXME: This should be replaced with a real .td file alias mechanism. ----
3910 // Also, MatchInstructionImpl should actually *do* the EmitInstruction ----
3911 // call. ----
3912 const char *Repl = StringSwitch(Op.getToken()) 0
3913 .Case("finit", "fninit") 0
3914 .Case("fsave", "fnsave") 0
3915 .Case("fstcw", "fnstcw") 0
3916 .Case("fstcww", "fnstcw") 0
3917 .Case("fstenv", "fnstenv") 0
3918 .Case("fstsw", "fnstsw") 0
3919 .Case("fstsww", "fnstsw") 0
3920 .Case("fclex", "fnclex") 0
3921 .Default(nullptr); 0
3922 if (Repl) { 0
3923 MCInst Inst; 0
3924 Inst.setOpcode(X86::WAIT); 0
3925 Inst.setLoc(IDLoc); 0
3926 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
3927 emitInstruction(Inst, Operands, Out); 0
3928 Operands[0] = X86Operand::CreateToken(Repl, IDLoc); 0
3929 } 0
3930 } 0
3931 ----
3932 bool X86AsmParser::ErrorMissingFeature(SMLoc IDLoc, 0
3933 const FeatureBitset &MissingFeatures, ----
3934 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
3935 assert(MissingFeatures.any() && "Unknown missing feature!"); 0
3936 SmallString<126> Msg; 0
3937 raw_svector_ostream OS(Msg); 0
3938 OS << "instruction requires:"; 0
3939 for (unsigned i = 0, e = MissingFeatures.size(); i != e; ++i) { 0
3940 if (MissingFeatures[i]) 0
3941 OS << ' ' << getSubtargetFeatureName(i); 0
3942 } ----
3943 return Error(IDLoc, OS.str(), SMRange(), MatchingInlineAsm); 0
3944 } 0
3945 ----
3946 static unsigned getPrefixes(OperandVector &Operands) { 0
3947 unsigned Result = 0; 0
3948 X86Operand &Prefix = static_cast(*Operands.back()); 0
3949 if (Prefix.isPrefix()) { 0
3950 Result = Prefix.getPrefix(); 0
3951 Operands.pop_back(); 0
3952 } ----
3953 return Result; 0
3954 } ----
3955 ----
3956 unsigned X86AsmParser::checkTargetMatchPredicate(MCInst &Inst) { 0
3957 unsigned Opc = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
3958 const MCInstrDesc &MCID = MII.get(Opc); 0
3959 ----
3960 if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_EVEX && 0
3961 (MCID.TSFlags & X86II::EncodingMask) != X86II::EVEX) 0
3962 return Match_Unsupported; 0
3963 ----
3964 if ((ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX || 0
3965 ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX2 || 0
3966 ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX3) && 0
3967 (MCID.TSFlags & X86II::EncodingMask) != X86II::VEX) 0
3968 return Match_Unsupported; 0
3969 ----
3970 // These instructions are only available with {vex}, {vex2} or {vex3} prefix ----
3971 if (MCID.TSFlags & X86II::ExplicitVEXPrefix && 0
3972 (ForcedVEXEncoding != VEXEncoding_VEX && 0
3973 ForcedVEXEncoding != VEXEncoding_VEX2 && 0
3974 ForcedVEXEncoding != VEXEncoding_VEX3)) 0
3975 return Match_Unsupported; 0
3976 ----
3977 return Match_Success; 0
3978 } ----
3979 ----
3980 bool X86AsmParser::MatchAndEmitATTInstruction(SMLoc IDLoc, unsigned &Opcode, 0
3981 OperandVector &Operands, ----
3982 MCStreamer &Out, ----
3983 uint64_t &ErrorInfo, ----
3984 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
3985 assert(!Operands.empty() && "Unexpect empty operand list!"); 0
3986 assert((*Operands[0]).isToken() && "Leading operand should always be a mnemonic!"); 0
3987 SMRange EmptyRange = std::nullopt; 0
3988 ----
3989 // First, handle aliases that expand to multiple instructions. ----
3990 MatchFPUWaitAlias(IDLoc, static_cast(*Operands[0]), Operands, 0
3991 Out, MatchingInlineAsm); ----
3992 X86Operand &Op = static_cast(*Operands[0]); 0
3993 unsigned Prefixes = getPrefixes(Operands); 0
3994 ----
3995 MCInst Inst; 0
3996 ----
3997 // If VEX/EVEX encoding is forced, we need to pass the USE_* flag to the ----
3998 // encoder and printer. ----
3999 if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX) 0
4000 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX; 0
4001 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX2) 0
4002 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX2; 0
4003 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX3) 0
4004 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX3; 0
4005 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_EVEX) 0
4006 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_EVEX; 0
4007 ----
4008 // Set encoded flags for {disp8} and {disp32}. ----
4009 if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp8) 0
4010 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_DISP8; 0
4011 else if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp32) 0
4012 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_DISP32; 0
4013 ----
4014 if (Prefixes) 0
4015 Inst.setFlags(Prefixes); 0
4016 ----
4017 // In 16-bit mode, if data32 is specified, temporarily switch to 32-bit mode ----
4018 // when matching the instruction. ----
4019 if (ForcedDataPrefix == X86::Is32Bit) 0
4020 SwitchMode(X86::Is32Bit); 0
4021 // First, try a direct match. ----
4022 FeatureBitset MissingFeatures; 0
4023 unsigned OriginalError = MatchInstruction(Operands, Inst, ErrorInfo, 0
4024 MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm, ----
4025 isParsingIntelSyntax()); 0
4026 if (ForcedDataPrefix == X86::Is32Bit) { 0
4027 SwitchMode(X86::Is16Bit); 0
4028 ForcedDataPrefix = 0; 0
4029 } ----
4030 switch (OriginalError) { 0
4031 default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected match result!"); 0
4032 case Match_Success: 0
4033 if (!MatchingInlineAsm && validateInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4034 return true; 0
4035 // Some instructions need post-processing to, for example, tweak which ----
4036 // encoding is selected. Loop on it while changes happen so the ----
4037 // individual transformations can chain off each other. ----
4038 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4039 while (processInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4040 ; ----
4041 ----
4042 Inst.setLoc(IDLoc); 0
4043 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4044 emitInstruction(Inst, Operands, Out); 0
4045 Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
4046 return false; 0
4047 case Match_InvalidImmUnsignedi4: { 0
4048 SMLoc ErrorLoc = ((X86Operand &)*Operands[ErrorInfo]).getStartLoc(); 0
4049 if (ErrorLoc == SMLoc()) 0
4050 ErrorLoc = IDLoc; 0
4051 return Error(ErrorLoc, "immediate must be an integer in range [0, 15]", 0
4052 EmptyRange, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4053 } ----
4054 case Match_MissingFeature: 0
4055 return ErrorMissingFeature(IDLoc, MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4056 case Match_InvalidOperand: 0
4057 case Match_MnemonicFail: ----
4058 case Match_Unsupported: ----
4059 break; 0
4060 } ----
4061 if (Op.getToken().empty()) { 0
4062 Error(IDLoc, "instruction must have size higher than 0", EmptyRange, 0
4063 MatchingInlineAsm); ----
4064 return true; 0
4065 } ----
4066 ----
4067 // FIXME: Ideally, we would only attempt suffix matches for things which are ----
4068 // valid prefixes, and we could just infer the right unambiguous ----
4069 // type. However, that requires substantially more matcher support than the ----
4070 // following hack. ----
4071 ----
4072 // Change the operand to point to a temporary token. ----
4073 StringRef Base = Op.getToken(); 0
4074 SmallString<16> Tmp; 0
4075 Tmp += Base; 0
4076 Tmp += ' '; 0
4077 Op.setTokenValue(Tmp); 0
4078 ----
4079 // If this instruction starts with an 'f', then it is a floating point stack ----
4080 // instruction. These come in up to three forms for 32-bit, 64-bit, and ----
4081 // 80-bit floating point, which use the suffixes s,l,t respectively. ----
4082 // ----
4083 // Otherwise, we assume that this may be an integer instruction, which comes ----
4084 // in 8/16/32/64-bit forms using the b,w,l,q suffixes respectively. ----
4085 const char *Suffixes = Base[0] != 'f' ? "bwlq" : "slt\0"; 0
4086 // MemSize corresponding to Suffixes. { 8, 16, 32, 64 } { 32, 64, 80, 0 } ----
4087 const char *MemSize = Base[0] != 'f' ? "\x08\x10\x20\x40" : "\x20\x40\x50\0"; 0
4088 ----
4089 // Check for the various suffix matches. ----
4090 uint64_t ErrorInfoIgnore; ----
4091 FeatureBitset ErrorInfoMissingFeatures; // Init suppresses compiler warnings. 0
4092 unsigned Match[4]; ----
4093 ----
4094 // Some instruction like VPMULDQ is NOT the variant of VPMULD but a new one. ----
4095 // So we should make sure the suffix matcher only works for memory variant ----
4096 // that has the same size with the suffix. ----
4097 // FIXME: This flag is a workaround for legacy instructions that didn't ----
4098 // declare non suffix variant assembly. ----
4099 bool HasVectorReg = false; 0
4100 X86Operand *MemOp = nullptr; 0
4101 for (const auto &Op : Operands) { 0
4102 X86Operand *X86Op = static_cast(Op.get()); 0
4103 if (X86Op->isVectorReg()) 0
4104 HasVectorReg = true; 0
4105 else if (X86Op->isMem()) { 0
4106 MemOp = X86Op; 0
4107 assert(MemOp->Mem.Size == 0 && "Memory size always 0 under ATT syntax"); 0
4108 // Have we found an unqualified memory operand, ----
4109 // break. IA allows only one memory operand. ----
4110 break; 0
4111 } ----
4112 } ----
4113 ----
4114 for (unsigned I = 0, E = std::size(Match); I != E; ++I) { 0
4115 Tmp.back() = Suffixes[I]; 0
4116 if (MemOp && HasVectorReg) 0
4117 MemOp->Mem.Size = MemSize[I]; 0
4118 Match[I] = Match_MnemonicFail; 0
4119 if (MemOp || !HasVectorReg) { 0
4120 Match[I] = 0
4121 MatchInstruction(Operands, Inst, ErrorInfoIgnore, MissingFeatures, 0
4122 MatchingInlineAsm, isParsingIntelSyntax()); 0
4123 // If this returned as a missing feature failure, remember that. ----
4124 if (Match[I] == Match_MissingFeature) 0
4125 ErrorInfoMissingFeatures = MissingFeatures; 0
4126 } ----
4127 } ----
4128 ----
4129 // Restore the old token. ----
4130 Op.setTokenValue(Base); 0
4131 ----
4132 // If exactly one matched, then we treat that as a successful match (and the ----
4133 // instruction will already have been filled in correctly, since the failing ----
4134 // matches won't have modified it). ----
4135 unsigned NumSuccessfulMatches = llvm::count(Match, Match_Success); 0
4136 if (NumSuccessfulMatches == 1) { 0
4137 if (!MatchingInlineAsm && validateInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4138 return true; 0
4139 // Some instructions need post-processing to, for example, tweak which ----
4140 // encoding is selected. Loop on it while changes happen so the ----
4141 // individual transformations can chain off each other. ----
4142 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4143 while (processInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4144 ; ----
4145 ----
4146 Inst.setLoc(IDLoc); 0
4147 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4148 emitInstruction(Inst, Operands, Out); 0
4149 Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
4150 return false; 0
4151 } ----
4152 ----
4153 // Otherwise, the match failed, try to produce a decent error message. ----
4154 ----
4155 // If we had multiple suffix matches, then identify this as an ambiguous ----
4156 // match. ----
4157 if (NumSuccessfulMatches > 1) { 0
4158 char MatchChars[4]; ----
4159 unsigned NumMatches = 0; 0
4160 for (unsigned I = 0, E = std::size(Match); I != E; ++I) 0
4161 if (Match[I] == Match_Success) 0
4162 MatchChars[NumMatches++] = Suffixes[I]; 0
4163 ----
4164 SmallString<126> Msg; 0
4165 raw_svector_ostream OS(Msg); 0
4166 OS << "ambiguous instructions require an explicit suffix (could be "; 0
4167 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumMatches; ++i) { 0
4168 if (i != 0) 0
4169 OS << ", "; 0
4170 if (i + 1 == NumMatches) 0
4171 OS << "or "; 0
4172 OS << "'" << Base << MatchChars[i] << "'"; 0
4173 } ----
4174 OS << ")"; 0
4175 Error(IDLoc, OS.str(), EmptyRange, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4176 return true; 0
4177 } 0
4178 ----
4179 // Okay, we know that none of the variants matched successfully. ----
4180 ----
4181 // If all of the instructions reported an invalid mnemonic, then the original ----
4182 // mnemonic was invalid. ----
4183 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_MnemonicFail) == 4) { 0
4184 if (OriginalError == Match_MnemonicFail) 0
4185 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid instruction mnemonic '" + Base + "'", 0
4186 Op.getLocRange(), MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4187 ----
4188 if (OriginalError == Match_Unsupported) 0
4189 return Error(IDLoc, "unsupported instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4190 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4191 ----
4192 assert(OriginalError == Match_InvalidOperand && "Unexpected error"); 0
4193 // Recover location info for the operand if we know which was the problem. ----
4194 if (ErrorInfo != ~0ULL) { 0
4195 if (ErrorInfo >= Operands.size()) 0
4196 return Error(IDLoc, "too few operands for instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4197 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4198 ----
4199 X86Operand &Operand = (X86Operand &)*Operands[ErrorInfo]; 0
4200 if (Operand.getStartLoc().isValid()) { 0
4201 SMRange OperandRange = Operand.getLocRange(); 0
4202 return Error(Operand.getStartLoc(), "invalid operand for instruction", 0
4203 OperandRange, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4204 } ----
4205 } ----
4206 ----
4207 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid operand for instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4208 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4209 } ----
4210 ----
4211 // If one instruction matched as unsupported, report this as unsupported. ----
4212 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_Unsupported) == 1) { 0
4213 return Error(IDLoc, "unsupported instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4214 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4215 } ----
4216 ----
4217 // If one instruction matched with a missing feature, report this as a ----
4218 // missing feature. ----
4219 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_MissingFeature) == 1) { 0
4220 ErrorInfo = Match_MissingFeature; 0
4221 return ErrorMissingFeature(IDLoc, ErrorInfoMissingFeatures, 0
4222 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4223 } ----
4224 ----
4225 // If one instruction matched with an invalid operand, report this as an ----
4226 // operand failure. ----
4227 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_InvalidOperand) == 1) { 0
4228 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid operand for instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4229 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4230 } ----
4231 ----
4232 // If all of these were an outright failure, report it in a useless way. ----
4233 Error(IDLoc, "unknown use of instruction mnemonic without a size suffix", 0
4234 EmptyRange, MatchingInlineAsm); ----
4235 return true; 0
4236 } 0
4237 ----
4238 bool X86AsmParser::MatchAndEmitIntelInstruction(SMLoc IDLoc, unsigned &Opcode, 0
4239 OperandVector &Operands, ----
4240 MCStreamer &Out, ----
4241 uint64_t &ErrorInfo, ----
4242 bool MatchingInlineAsm) { ----
4243 assert(!Operands.empty() && "Unexpect empty operand list!"); 0
4244 assert((*Operands[0]).isToken() && "Leading operand should always be a mnemonic!"); 0
4245 StringRef Mnemonic = (static_cast(*Operands[0])).getToken(); 0
4246 SMRange EmptyRange = std::nullopt; 0
4247 StringRef Base = (static_cast(*Operands[0])).getToken(); 0
4248 unsigned Prefixes = getPrefixes(Operands); 0
4249 ----
4250 // First, handle aliases that expand to multiple instructions. ----
4251 MatchFPUWaitAlias(IDLoc, static_cast(*Operands[0]), Operands, Out, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4252 X86Operand &Op = static_cast(*Operands[0]); 0
4253 ----
4254 MCInst Inst; 0
4255 ----
4256 // If VEX/EVEX encoding is forced, we need to pass the USE_* flag to the ----
4257 // encoder and printer. ----
4258 if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX) 0
4259 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX; 0
4260 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX2) 0
4261 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX2; 0
4262 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_VEX3) 0
4263 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_VEX3; 0
4264 else if (ForcedVEXEncoding == VEXEncoding_EVEX) 0
4265 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_EVEX; 0
4266 ----
4267 // Set encoded flags for {disp8} and {disp32}. ----
4268 if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp8) 0
4269 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_DISP8; 0
4270 else if (ForcedDispEncoding == DispEncoding_Disp32) 0
4271 Prefixes |= X86::IP_USE_DISP32; 0
4272 ----
4273 if (Prefixes) 0
4274 Inst.setFlags(Prefixes); 0
4275 ----
4276 // Find one unsized memory operand, if present. ----
4277 X86Operand *UnsizedMemOp = nullptr; 0
4278 for (const auto &Op : Operands) { 0
4279 X86Operand *X86Op = static_cast(Op.get()); 0
4280 if (X86Op->isMemUnsized()) { 0
4281 UnsizedMemOp = X86Op; 0
4282 // Have we found an unqualified memory operand, ----
4283 // break. IA allows only one memory operand. ----
4284 break; 0
4285 } ----
4286 } ----
4287 ----
4288 // Allow some instructions to have implicitly pointer-sized operands. This is ----
4289 // compatible with gas. ----
4290 if (UnsizedMemOp) { 0
4291 static const char *const PtrSizedInstrs[] = {"call", "jmp", "push"}; ----
4292 for (const char *Instr : PtrSizedInstrs) { 0
4293 if (Mnemonic == Instr) { 0
4294 UnsizedMemOp->Mem.Size = getPointerWidth(); 0
4295 break; 0
4296 } ----
4297 } ----
4298 } ----
4299 ----
4300 SmallVector Match; 0
4301 FeatureBitset ErrorInfoMissingFeatures; 0
4302 FeatureBitset MissingFeatures; 0
4303 ----
4304 // If unsized push has immediate operand we should default the default pointer ----
4305 // size for the size. ----
4306 if (Mnemonic == "push" && Operands.size() == 2) { 0
4307 auto *X86Op = static_cast(Operands[1].get()); 0
4308 if (X86Op->isImm()) { 0
4309 // If it's not a constant fall through and let remainder take care of it. ----
4310 const auto *CE = dyn_cast(X86Op->getImm()); 0
4311 unsigned Size = getPointerWidth(); 0
4312 if (CE && 0
4313 (isIntN(Size, CE->getValue()) || isUIntN(Size, CE->getValue()))) { 0
4314 SmallString<16> Tmp; 0
4315 Tmp += Base; 0
4316 Tmp += (is64BitMode()) 0
4317 ? "q" ----
4318 : (is32BitMode()) ? "l" : (is16BitMode()) ? "w" : " "; 0
4319 Op.setTokenValue(Tmp); 0
4320 // Do match in ATT mode to allow explicit suffix usage. ----
4321 Match.push_back(MatchInstruction(Operands, Inst, ErrorInfo, 0
4322 MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm, ----
4323 false /*isParsingIntelSyntax()*/)); ----
4324 Op.setTokenValue(Base); 0
4325 } 0
4326 } ----
4327 } ----
4328 ----
4329 // If an unsized memory operand is present, try to match with each memory ----
4330 // operand size. In Intel assembly, the size is not part of the instruction ----
4331 // mnemonic. ----
4332 if (UnsizedMemOp && UnsizedMemOp->isMemUnsized()) { 0
4333 static const unsigned MopSizes[] = {8, 16, 32, 64, 80, 128, 256, 512}; ----
4334 for (unsigned Size : MopSizes) { 0
4335 UnsizedMemOp->Mem.Size = Size; 0
4336 uint64_t ErrorInfoIgnore; ----
4337 unsigned LastOpcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
4338 unsigned M = MatchInstruction(Operands, Inst, ErrorInfoIgnore, 0
4339 MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm, ----
4340 isParsingIntelSyntax()); 0
4341 if (Match.empty() || LastOpcode != Inst.getOpcode()) 0
4342 Match.push_back(M); 0
4343 ----
4344 // If this returned as a missing feature failure, remember that. ----
4345 if (Match.back() == Match_MissingFeature) 0
4346 ErrorInfoMissingFeatures = MissingFeatures; 0
4347 } ----
4348 ----
4349 // Restore the size of the unsized memory operand if we modified it. ----
4350 UnsizedMemOp->Mem.Size = 0; 0
4351 } ----
4352 ----
4353 // If we haven't matched anything yet, this is not a basic integer or FPU ----
4354 // operation. There shouldn't be any ambiguity in our mnemonic table, so try ----
4355 // matching with the unsized operand. ----
4356 if (Match.empty()) { 0
4357 Match.push_back(MatchInstruction( 0
4358 Operands, Inst, ErrorInfo, MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm, ----
4359 isParsingIntelSyntax())); 0
4360 // If this returned as a missing feature failure, remember that. ----
4361 if (Match.back() == Match_MissingFeature) 0
4362 ErrorInfoMissingFeatures = MissingFeatures; 0
4363 } ----
4364 ----
4365 // Restore the size of the unsized memory operand if we modified it. ----
4366 if (UnsizedMemOp) 0
4367 UnsizedMemOp->Mem.Size = 0; 0
4368 ----
4369 // If it's a bad mnemonic, all results will be the same. ----
4370 if (Match.back() == Match_MnemonicFail) { 0
4371 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid instruction mnemonic '" + Mnemonic + "'", 0
4372 Op.getLocRange(), MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4373 } ----
4374 ----
4375 unsigned NumSuccessfulMatches = llvm::count(Match, Match_Success); 0
4376 ----
4377 // If matching was ambiguous and we had size information from the frontend, ----
4378 // try again with that. This handles cases like "movxz eax, m8/m16". ----
4379 if (UnsizedMemOp && NumSuccessfulMatches > 1 && 0
4380 UnsizedMemOp->getMemFrontendSize()) { 0
4381 UnsizedMemOp->Mem.Size = UnsizedMemOp->getMemFrontendSize(); 0
4382 unsigned M = MatchInstruction( 0
4383 Operands, Inst, ErrorInfo, MissingFeatures, MatchingInlineAsm, ----
4384 isParsingIntelSyntax()); 0
4385 if (M == Match_Success) 0
4386 NumSuccessfulMatches = 1; 0
4387 ----
4388 // Add a rewrite that encodes the size information we used from the ----
4389 // frontend. ----
4390 InstInfo->AsmRewrites->emplace_back( 0
4391 AOK_SizeDirective, UnsizedMemOp->getStartLoc(), 0
4392 /*Len=*/0, UnsizedMemOp->getMemFrontendSize()); 0
4393 } ----
4394 ----
4395 // If exactly one matched, then we treat that as a successful match (and the ----
4396 // instruction will already have been filled in correctly, since the failing ----
4397 // matches won't have modified it). ----
4398 if (NumSuccessfulMatches == 1) { 0
4399 if (!MatchingInlineAsm && validateInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4400 return true; 0
4401 // Some instructions need post-processing to, for example, tweak which ----
4402 // encoding is selected. Loop on it while changes happen so the individual ----
4403 // transformations can chain off each other. ----
4404 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4405 while (processInstruction(Inst, Operands)) 0
4406 ; ----
4407 Inst.setLoc(IDLoc); 0
4408 if (!MatchingInlineAsm) 0
4409 emitInstruction(Inst, Operands, Out); 0
4410 Opcode = Inst.getOpcode(); 0
4411 return false; 0
4412 } else if (NumSuccessfulMatches > 1) { 0
4413 assert(UnsizedMemOp && 0
4414 "multiple matches only possible with unsized memory operands"); ----
4415 return Error(UnsizedMemOp->getStartLoc(), 0
4416 "ambiguous operand size for instruction '" + Mnemonic + "\'", 0
4417 UnsizedMemOp->getLocRange()); 0
4418 } ----
4419 ----
4420 // If one instruction matched as unsupported, report this as unsupported. ----
4421 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_Unsupported) == 1) { 0
4422 return Error(IDLoc, "unsupported instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4423 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4424 } ----
4425 ----
4426 // If one instruction matched with a missing feature, report this as a ----
4427 // missing feature. ----
4428 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_MissingFeature) == 1) { 0
4429 ErrorInfo = Match_MissingFeature; 0
4430 return ErrorMissingFeature(IDLoc, ErrorInfoMissingFeatures, 0
4431 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4432 } ----
4433 ----
4434 // If one instruction matched with an invalid operand, report this as an ----
4435 // operand failure. ----
4436 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_InvalidOperand) == 1) { 0
4437 return Error(IDLoc, "invalid operand for instruction", EmptyRange, 0
4438 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4439 } ----
4440 ----
4441 if (llvm::count(Match, Match_InvalidImmUnsignedi4) == 1) { 0
4442 SMLoc ErrorLoc = ((X86Operand &)*Operands[ErrorInfo]).getStartLoc(); 0
4443 if (ErrorLoc == SMLoc()) 0
4444 ErrorLoc = IDLoc; 0
4445 return Error(ErrorLoc, "immediate must be an integer in range [0, 15]", 0
4446 EmptyRange, MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4447 } ----
4448 ----
4449 // If all of these were an outright failure, report it in a useless way. ----
4450 return Error(IDLoc, "unknown instruction mnemonic", EmptyRange, 0
4451 MatchingInlineAsm); 0
4452 } 0
4453 ----
4454 bool X86AsmParser::OmitRegisterFromClobberLists(unsigned RegNo) { 0
4455 return X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::SEGMENT_REGRegClassID].contains(RegNo); 0
4456 } ----
4457 ----
4458 bool X86AsmParser::ParseDirective(AsmToken DirectiveID) { 0
4459 MCAsmParser &Parser = getParser(); 0
4460 StringRef IDVal = DirectiveID.getIdentifier(); 0
4461 if (IDVal.startswith(".arch")) 0
4462 return parseDirectiveArch(); 0
4463 if (IDVal.startswith(".code")) 0
4464 return ParseDirectiveCode(IDVal, DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4465 else if (IDVal.startswith(".att_syntax")) { 0
4466 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
4467 if (Parser.getTok().getString() == "prefix") 0
4468 Parser.Lex(); 0
4469 else if (Parser.getTok().getString() == "noprefix") 0
4470 return Error(DirectiveID.getLoc(), "'.att_syntax noprefix' is not " 0
4471 "supported: registers must have a " ----
4472 "'%' prefix in .att_syntax"); 0
4473 } ----
4474 getParser().setAssemblerDialect(0); 0
4475 return false; 0
4476 } else if (IDVal.startswith(".intel_syntax")) { 0
4477 getParser().setAssemblerDialect(1); 0
4478 if (getLexer().isNot(AsmToken::EndOfStatement)) { 0
4479 if (Parser.getTok().getString() == "noprefix") 0
4480 Parser.Lex(); 0
4481 else if (Parser.getTok().getString() == "prefix") 0
4482 return Error(DirectiveID.getLoc(), "'.intel_syntax prefix' is not " 0
4483 "supported: registers must not have " ----
4484 "a '%' prefix in .intel_syntax"); 0
4485 } ----
4486 return false; 0
4487 } else if (IDVal == ".nops") 0
4488 return parseDirectiveNops(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4489 else if (IDVal == ".even") 0
4490 return parseDirectiveEven(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4491 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_proc") 0
4492 return parseDirectiveFPOProc(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4493 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_setframe") 0
4494 return parseDirectiveFPOSetFrame(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4495 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_pushreg") 0
4496 return parseDirectiveFPOPushReg(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4497 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_stackalloc") 0
4498 return parseDirectiveFPOStackAlloc(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4499 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_stackalign") 0
4500 return parseDirectiveFPOStackAlign(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4501 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_endprologue") 0
4502 return parseDirectiveFPOEndPrologue(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4503 else if (IDVal == ".cv_fpo_endproc") 0
4504 return parseDirectiveFPOEndProc(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0
4505 else if (IDVal == ".seh_pushreg" || 0
4506 (Parser.isParsingMasm() && IDVal.equals_insensitive(".pushreg"))) 0
4507 return parseDirectiveSEHPushReg(DirectiveID.getLoc()); 0

4532 bool X86AsmParser::parseDirectiveNops(SMLoc L) { 0
4533 int64_t NumBytes = 0, Control = 0; 0
4534 SMLoc NumBytesLoc, ControlLoc; 0
4535 const MCSubtargetInfo& STI = getSTI(); 0

4556 return false; 0

4560 getParser().getStreamer().emitNops(NumBytes, Control, L, STI); 0
4561 ----
4562 return false; 0
4563 } ----

4691 bool X86AsmParser::parseSEHRegisterNumber(unsigned RegClassID, 0
4692 MCRegister &RegNo) { ----
4693 SMLoc startLoc = getLexer().getLoc(); 0
4694 const MCRegisterInfo *MRI = getContext().getRegisterInfo(); 0
4695 ----
4696 // Try parsing the argument as a register first. ----
4697 if (getLexer().getTok().isNot(AsmToken::Integer)) { 0
4698 SMLoc endLoc; 0
4699 if (parseRegister(RegNo, startLoc, endLoc)) 0
4700 return true; 0
4701 ----
4702 if (!X86MCRegisterClasses[RegClassID].contains(RegNo)) { 0
4703 return Error(startLoc, 0
4704 "register is not supported for use with this directive"); 0
4705 } ----
4706 } else { ----
4707 // Otherwise, an integer number matching the encoding of the desired ----
4708 // register may appear. ----
4709 int64_t EncodedReg; ----
4710 if (getParser().parseAbsoluteExpression(EncodedReg)) 0
4711 return true; 0
4712 ----
4713 // The SEH register number is the same as the encoding register number. Map ----
4714 // from the encoding back to the LLVM register number. ----
4715 RegNo = 0; 0
4716 for (MCPhysReg Reg : X86MCRegisterClasses[RegClassID]) { 0
4717 if (MRI->getEncodingValue(Reg) == EncodedReg) { 0
4718 RegNo = Reg; 0
4719 break; 0
4720 } ----
4721 } ----
4722 if (RegNo == 0) { 0
4723 return Error(startLoc, 0
4724 "incorrect register number for use with this directive"); 0
4725 } ----
4726 } ----
4727 ----
4728 return false; 0
4729 } ----
